{"award_age":49.0,"bio_image":"full\/2f76ca945c98bda109bb4d4f6e7ce9eccbfb6387.jpg","category":"Physics","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1931-09-29T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/3\/30\/James-cronin.jpg\/220px-James-cronin.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_Cronin","mini_bio":"<p><b>James Watson Cronin<\/b> (born September 29, 1931) is an <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States\" title=\"United States\">American<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nuclear_physics\" title=\"Nuclear physics\">nuclear physicist<\/a>.<\/p><p>Cronin was born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chicago,_Illinois\" title=\"Chicago, Illinois\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Chicago, Illinois<\/a> and attended <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Southern_Methodist_University\" title=\"Southern Methodist University\">Southern Methodist University<\/a> in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dallas,_Texas\" title=\"Dallas, Texas\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Dallas, Texas<\/a>. Cronin and co-researcher <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Val_Logsdon_Fitch\" title=\"Val Logsdon Fitch\">Val Logsdon Fitch<\/a> were awarded the 1980 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physics\">Nobel Prize in Physics<\/a> for a 1964 experiment that proved that certain subatomic reactions do not adhere to fundamental symmetry principles. Specifically, they proved, by examining the decay of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Kaon\" title=\"Kaon\">kaons<\/a>, that a reaction run in reverse does not merely retrace the path of the original reaction, which showed that the interactions of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Subatomic_particle\" title=\"Subatomic particle\">subatomic particles<\/a> are not indifferent to time. Thus the phenomenon of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/CP_violation\" title=\"CP violation\">CP violation<\/a> was discovered.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_Cronin#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_Cronin#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_Cronin#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_Cronin#cite_note-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Cronin received the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ernest_Orlando_Lawrence_Award\" title=\"Ernest Orlando Lawrence Award\">Ernest Orlando Lawrence Award<\/a> in 1976 for major experimental contributions to particle physics including fundamental work on weak interactions culminating in the discovery of asymmetry under time reversal. In 1999, he was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/National_Medal_of_Science\" title=\"National Medal of Science\">National Medal of Science<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_Cronin#cite_note-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Cronin is <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Professor\" title=\"Professor\">Professor<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Emeritus\" title=\"Emeritus\">Emeritus<\/a> at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Chicago\" title=\"University of Chicago\">University of Chicago<\/a> and a spokesperson emeritus for the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Pierre_Auger_Observatory\" title=\"Pierre Auger Observatory\">Auger<\/a> project. Cronin is a member of the Board of Sponsors of The <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Bulletin_of_the_Atomic_Scientists\" title=\"Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists\">Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists<\/a>.<\/p>","name":"James Cronin","place_of_birth":"Chicago, Illinois ,  USA","place_of_death":null,"text":"James Cronin , Physics, 1980","year":1980.0}